    <div class=".poem">
        <h1>या घट भीतर / In This Body</h1>
        <h3>कबीर / Kabir</h3>
        <p>8 Sept, 2024</p>
        <hr class=hr>
        <p>
            <br>
            या घट भीतर बाग़ बगीचे <br>
            या ही में सिरजनहारा <br>
            ढूंढे रे ढूंढे अंधियारा <br>
            <br>
            या घट भीतर सात समंदर <br>
            या ही में नौ लख तारा <br>
            ढूंढे रे ढूंढे अंधियारा <br>
            <br>
            या घट भीतर हीरा और मोती <br>
            या ही में परखनहारा <br>
            ढूंढे रे ढूंढे अंधियारा <br>
            <br>
            या घट भीतर अनहद गरजे <br>
            या ही में उठत फुवारा <br>
            ढूंढे रे ढूंढे अंधियारा <br>
            <br>
            कहे कबीरा सुनो भाई साधो <br>
            या ही में गुरु है हमारा <br>
            ढूंढे रे ढूंढे अंधियारा <br>
            <br>
        </p>

        <hr class=hr>
    </div>
    <div class="notes">
        <p>
            <br>
            This poem is translated from Gujarati. Credits - Vipul Rikhi, Shabnam Virmani
            <br><br>
            Renowned Gujarati writer Dhruv Bhatt recounts the moment when this poem was born. 
            Once he was walking on a hot day in a poor rural belt in coastal Saurashtra. 
            From a distance he saw an old man wearing a tattered dhoti struggling to till a harsh, 
            rocky earth with a heavy plough, while the sun beat down mercilessly. 
            Feeling deeply sympathetic to the old man's plight, Dhruv Dada gently asked him as he passed by, 
            Dada, kem chhe? (How are you?) The old man lifted his face and flashing a beatific smile at Dhruv Dada crooned, 
            'I'm doing just great!' Utterly taken aback and brought face to face with his own assumptions, 
            in that moment a song took shape in his heart.
        </p>
    </div>
